# View Transitions

## How It Works

`TransitionLink` intercepts clicks, calls `document.startViewTransition()`, then `router.push()`. The `ViewTransitionHandler` component resolves the transition promise when the new page renders (via `useLayoutEffect` on pathname change).

Back navigation is handled by an inline `<script>` in `layout.tsx` `<head>` that registers a `popstate` handler BEFORE Next.js hydrates. This is critical — Next.js's own popstate handler runs first otherwise, completing navigation before the transition captures the old state.

## Safety Timeout

A 150ms timeout auto-resolves the transition if the page hasn't rendered yet. This prevents the UI from freezing.

## Direction

`data-vt-direction` attribute on `<html>` is set to `"forward"` or `"back"`. CSS uses this for directional slide animations.

## Persistent Elements

Nav and footer have `viewTransitionName: "site-nav"` / `"site-footer"` with `animation: none` so they stay still during transitions.

## Common Pitfall

Duplicate `viewTransitionName` values on a page silently abort ALL transitions. Always include the content type in names: `${type}-${element}-${slug}`.
